<paragraph blockId="38.[151,1436,152,1098]" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">
<emphasis box="[198,330,952,977]" italics="true" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">Etymology.</emphasis>
From the Greek 
<emphasis box="[536,614,952,977]" italics="true" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">chalco</emphasis>
“bronze” and Greek 
<emphasis box="[870,963,952,977]" italics="true" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">cephalo</emphasis>
“head”, in reference to the coloration of the head.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="38.[151,1436,152,1098]" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">
<emphasis box="[198,301,1032,1057]" italics="true" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">Remarks</emphasis>
. This species is known only from the female and is quite small. The mesosoma is only slightly longer than broad. In two of the 
<typeStatus box="[537,638,1072,1098]" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">paratype</typeStatus>
specimens, the mesosoma is actually slightly broader than long.
</paragraph>
